'''Southern Adventist University''' is a [[college]] in [[Collegedale, Tennessee]], owned and operated by the [[Southern Union Conference of Seventh-day Adventists]]. ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' categorizes it as a Southern Regional College, and the magazine has consistently ranked it as one of the top-tier schools in that category.<ref name="USNews">[http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/southern-adventist-3518 "''US News'' Best Colleges 2011", ranked no. 31, Southern Adventist University] Retrieved 2011-05-31.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal
  | title = Student Scene: Southern Adventist University Ranked Among The Top 25 Colleges in the South
  | journal = The Chattanoogan.com
  | location = Chattanooga
  | date = September 13, 2010
  | url = http://www.chattanoogan.com/articles/article_183948.asp
  | accessdate = 2011-11-10 }} "Southern Adventist University is ranked one of the <U+201C>Best Baccalaureate Colleges<U+201D> in the South by the ''U.S. News & World Report'' in its 2010 <U+201C>America<U+2019>s Best Colleges<U+201D> edition. This is the eighth year Southern has been listed as a Top Tier college. ... Southern was listed as number 24." Retrieved 2011-05-31.</ref> Southern Adventist University occupies a {{convert|1000|acre|km2}} campus in a rural setting in the [[Tennessee River Valley]].<ref name="USNews"/> 

It was founded in [[1892 in the United States|1892]] in Graysville, Tennessee, as Graysville Academy and was the first Adventist school in the [[Southern United States|southern U.S.]] Due to the need for additional space for expansion the school relocated in 1916 and was renamed Southern Junior College. In 1944 Southern began awarding baccalaureate degrees and was renamed Southern Missionary College. In 1996 the institution started conferring Masters degrees and adopted its current name.  

Southern offers baccalaureate, associate and master's degrees.<ref name="USNews"/> It is accredited by multiple organizations including the Commission on Colleges of the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools. Its Institute of Archaeology offers an undergraduate degree in biblical archaeology; Southern is one of only two schools which offer the degree. It is known for its emphasis on conservative religious and [[social conservatism in the United States|social practices]],<ref name=sptm08-07-02>{{cite news|last=Downing|first=Lawrence|title=Confronting the Challenges in Adventist Education|url=http://spectrummagazine.org/node/742|accessdate=2011-04-19|newspaper=[[Spectrum Blog]]|date=2 July 2008}}</ref> and is considered the most conservative of the [[Seventh-day Adventist]] schools in [[North American Division of Seventh-day Adventists|North America]].<ref name="NAD-southern-most-conservative">{{cite web|last=Hughes|first=Tom|title=ISSUES: Creative Arts Ministries and the Spirit of Prophecy|url=http://www.childmin.com/printable.php?lang=eng&index=41|work=Children's ministry website|publisher=[[North American Division of Seventh-day Adventists]]|accessdate=2011-04-30}}</ref> The college operates a [[radio station]] ([[WSMC-FM]]), a health-food store and a wellness center.  Enrollment was 3,053 students in 2010, its highest level to date.<ref>{{Cite journal
  | editor = Jarod, Keith 
  | title = Enrollment Surpasses 3000
  | journal = Southern Factor (employee newsletter)
  | page = 1
  | publisher = Southern Adventist University,  
  | location = Collegedale, TN
  | date = October, 2010
  | url = https://www.southern.edu/marketing/Documents/Factor/Factor_oct_2010.pdf
  | accessdate = 2011-11-10}}</ref>

==History==
Southern's roots stem from the establishment of Graysville Academy in [[Graysville, Tennessee]], in 1892,<ref>{{Cite book
  | last = Land
  | first = Gary
  | title = Historical Dictionary of Seventh-day Adventists
  | publisher = Scarecrow Press 
  | year = 2005 
  | location = Lanham MD
  | pages = 281 
  | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=fFYFLksIywcC&pg=PA281&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false
  | isbn = 0810853450}}
</ref> in a part of the South much affected by the [[American Civil War]]. The area saw the [[battle of Chickamauga]] and the [[Chattanooga campaign]], and was the staging ground for [[William T. Sherman|Sherman]]'s [[Atlanta campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.battlesforchattanooga.com/open.html |title=History |publisher=The Battles For Chattanooga Museum|date= |accessdate=2011-09-11}}</ref> The Academy was privately funded at first, with no financial support from the Adventist church.<ref name="pettibone">Pettibone, Dennis (1992) ''A Century of Challenge: The Story of Southern College 1892-1992'', pp. 9-60</ref> In 1897 it was renamed the Southern Industrial School and then Southern Training School in 1901. The school moved to the community of Thatcher's Switch in 1916, renaming it Collegedale.<ref>{{Cite book
