===Notable alumni===
*[[Jim Davis (North Carolina politician)|Jim Davis]], state senator
*[[Clifford Goldstein]], author and editor
*[[Dwight Nelson]], pastor
*[[Cherie Priest]], novelist and blogger
*[[Mathew Staver]], founder and Chairman of [[Liberty Counsel]]

The Wedgwood Trio, an [[Folk music#Folk music in the 1960's|American folk group]] founded at [[Newbold College]] in England,<ref name="sanctuary"/> has been credited with introducing contemporary sounds into popular Adventist music.<ref name="Land">Land, Gary (2005) [http://books.google.ca/books?id=fFYFLksIywcC&pg=PA207&f=false ''Historical Dictionary of Seventh-day Adventists''] Lanham, MD: Scarecrow Press. p.207</ref> The ensemble, Bob Summerour, Don Vollmer and Jerry Hoyle, arrived in America in 1965<ref name ="Johnsson">Johnsson, William G. [http://www.adventistarchives.org/docs/RH/RH19970717-V174-29__C.pdf#view=fit "The Sound of Wedgwood"]. ''Adventist Review'', July 17, 1997, p. 13. Retrieved 2011-11-08.</ref> and attended and graduated from Southern Missionary College. They achieved widespread popularity in the denomination<ref name = "Land" /> due to their association with the [[Voice of Prophecy]]'s camp meeting circuit.<ref name = "Glendale" >[http://www.adventistarchives.org/docs/PUR/PUR19670724-V67-03__B.pdf#view=fit "Wedgwood Trio to Present Concert at Glendale Church"], ''Pacific Union Recorder'', July 24, 1967, p. 6. Retrieved 2011-11-08.</ref> In 1969, they returned to their alma mater to put on a concert.<ref>{{Citation
 | last=
 | first=
 | title=Pictorial/Stories
 | journal=Southern Tidings
 | volume=63
 | issue=7
 | year=1969
 | pages=25
 | url=http://www.adventistarchives.org/docs/SUW/SUW19690701-V63-07__B.pdf#view=fit
 | accessdate=2011-11-08
 }}</ref><!--Material has been rewritten since request for rewrite was made --> They performed from Massachusetts to Florida, in California, the Midwest, the Northwest and also in Canada.<ref name = "Glendale" /> Malcolm Bull and Keith Lockhart state that "[t]hey transformed the sound of Adventist popular music at the same time as English bands like The Beatles were breaking revolutionary new ground in the wider musical world."<ref name="sanctuary">{{cite book | last1 = Bull | first1 = Malcolm  | last2 = Lockhart| first2 = Keith | title = Seeking a Sanctuary: Seventh-day Adventism and the American Dream | publisher = Indiana University Press | location = Bloomington | year = 2007 | isbn = 0253218683 |page=[http://books.google.ca/books?id=ACUBSUGQCMYC&pg=PA226&f=false 226]}}</ref> In the early 1970s their career was brought to a halt when Adventist college presidents began banning them from their campuses.<ref name ="Johnsson"/> Twenty years later they re-united and resumed their musical career, complementing their other careers as psychiatrist (Summerour), church pastor (Vollmer) and clinical psychologist (Hoyle).<ref name="shultz09">{{Citation |last=Shultz |first=Dan |month= ''c.''March |year=2009|url=http://www.iamaonline.com/history/Wedgwood%20Trio.htm  |title=The Wedgwood Trio  |work=SDA Music History  |publisher= International Adventist Musicians Association  |accessdate=2011-11-11 }}</ref> The re-united trio issued several successful music CDs<ref name="shultz09"/> and re-gained the approval of Adventist church leaders and college presidents.<ref name="Johnsson"/>

